In this statement, the President commemorates the 20th anniversary of the Fourth World Conference on Women. He reaffirms the importance of women's empowerment and their full participation in society, including decision-making processes and access to power. The President highlights the progress made in the past 20 years towards gender equality in the United States, such as the reauthorization of the Violence Against Women Act and the Affordable Care Act. However, he acknowledges that there is still work to be done, as women and girls face violence, discrimination, and limited educational opportunities. The President discusses various initiatives aimed at advancing women's empowerment and education, addressing violence against women, and promoting job training and apprenticeships for women. He emphasizes the importance of supporting civil society and working towards a world where every woman and girl can enjoy their rights and freedoms.